           <!-- #comment-600 --> 
           <ul class="children"> 
            <li class="comment even depth-3 highlander-comment" id="li-comment-626"> 
             <div id="comment-626" class="clear"> 
              <div class="comment-meta">
                Aisha 
               <div class="comment-date">
                February 22, 2015
               </div> 
               <img alt="" src="http://0.gravatar.com/avatar/0e0d6b7c7d84cb028d00acdb2a95c5e6?s=55&amp;d=identicon&amp;r=G" class="avatar avatar-55" height="55" width="55"> 
              </div>
              <!-- .comment-meta --> 
              <div class="comment-content"> 
               <p>As a graduate of Willamette University (with a B.A. in theatre), I had very little UN “stage time” during my four years there. Every senior project done by a technician involved that technician leading their respective area of a mainstage show. In my four years there, I was in a mainstage show every semester; my senior project was based on performance. I was also gifted the opportunity to write an adaptation of a historical play and direct the show on my own. I graduated and ended up using the skills I gained in a scene design class (required for my major) to get a paid gig designing the set for a Shakespearean festival. I watched other students design sets and costumes, direct, act, light…and now, I keep up with them on Facebook and am constantly amazed by what a high percentage of those same students are still making a living in the industry.</p> 
               <p id="comment-like-626" data-liked="comment-not-liked" class="comment-likes comment-not-liked"><a href="http://onstageblog.com/2015/02/19/the-best-b-a-in-theatre-programs-in-the-country-in-2015/?like_comment=626&amp;_wpnonce=ca0ec72799" class="comment-like-link needs-login" rel="nofollow" data-blog="71050352"><span>Like</span></a><span id="comment-like-count-626" class="comment-like-feedback">Liked by <a href="#" class="view-likers" data-like-count="1">1 person</a></span></p> 
               <div class="reply"> 
               </div>
               <!-- .reply --> 
              </div> 
             </div>
             <!-- #comment-626 --> </li>
            <!-- #comment-## --> 
            <li class="comment odd alt depth-3 highlander-comment" id="li-comment-674"> 
             <div id="comment-674" class="clear"> 
              <div class="comment-meta">
                Essie 
               <div class="comment-date">
                February 24, 2015
               </div> 
               <img alt="" src="http://1.gravatar.com/avatar/1953825bbf8869089b174dc012ba627a?s=55&amp;d=identicon&amp;r=G" class="avatar avatar-55" height="55" width="55"> 
              </div>
              <!-- .comment-meta --> 
              <div class="comment-content"> 
               <p>At the schools on the list from the article or Northwestern, Fordham, Yale and Brown? Certainly at Brown, undergraduates get almost all of the stage time as Brown is primarily focused on its undergraduate population (I am a graduate of Brown with a degree in Theater Arts)</p> 
               <p id="comment-like-674" data-liked="comment-not-liked" class="comment-likes comment-not-liked"><a href="http://onstageblog.com/2015/02/19/the-best-b-a-in-theatre-programs-in-the-country-in-2015/?like_comment=674&amp;_wpnonce=27b161be39" class="comment-like-link needs-login" rel="nofollow" data-blog="71050352"><span>Like</span></a><span id="comment-like-count-674" class="comment-like-feedback">Like</span></p> 
               <div class="reply"> 
               </div>
               <!-- .reply --> 
              </div> 
             </div>
             <!-- #comment-674 --> </li>
            <!-- #comment-## --> 
            <li class="comment even depth-3 highlander-comment" id="li-comment-675"> 
             <div id="comment-675" class="clear"> 
              <div class="comment-meta">
                Josephine Clarke 
               <div class="comment-date">
                February 24, 2015
               </div> 
               <img alt="" src="http://1.gravatar.com/avatar/7508ce75dd07b7b3cc57f431ed7a9515?s=55&amp;d=identicon&amp;r=G" class="avatar avatar-55" height="55" width="55"> 
              </div>
              <!-- .comment-meta --> 
              <div class="comment-content"> 
               <p>Northwestern has around 50 entirely student produced/directed/designed student theatre productions each year and around 10-15 mainstage faculty run productions. The amount of stage time actors get there and amount of work and experience designers get is more than any other school I have seen — BA or BFA.</p> 
               <p id="comment-like-675" data-liked="comment-not-liked" class="comment-likes comment-not-liked"><a href="http://onstageblog.com/2015/02/19/the-best-b-a-in-theatre-programs-in-the-country-in-2015/?like_comment=675&amp;_wpnonce=8da06eb841" class="comment-like-link needs-login" rel="nofollow" data-blog="71050352"><span>Like</span></a><span id="comment-like-count-675" class="comment-like-feedback">Like</span></p> 
               <div class="reply"> 
               </div>
               <!-- .reply --> 
              </div> 
             </div>
             <!-- #comment-675 --> </li>
            <!-- #comment-## --> 
            <li class="comment byuser comment-author-selizabethhp odd alt depth-3 highlander-comment" id="li-comment-813"> 
             <div id="comment-813" class="clear"> 
              <div class="comment-meta"> 
               <a href="http://likeiceunderpressure.wordpress.com" rel="external nofollow" class="url">selizabethhp</a> 
               <div class="comment-date">
                February 27, 2015
               </div> 
               <img alt="" src="http://0.gravatar.com/avatar/33bb2c33e090b8a6a32aac9e85b5ad3b?s=55&amp;d=identicon&amp;r=G" class="avatar avatar-55" height="55" width="55"> 
              </div>
              <!-- .comment-meta --> 
              <div class="comment-content"> 
               <p>I’m a Fordham grad, and I can say that undergrads spend most of their time working on shows: in addition to four mainstage productions, we did an average of 20 studio productions a year, staffed almost entirely by students (there were some outside directors hired for playwriting productions and some outside designers–usually alums–who would come in if we were short on designers). Our student designers were so in demand that there was more work than they could take on. </p> 
               <p>That’s not even counting the number of readings, directing showcases, class showcases, one-time performances for guest artists… Acting majors may not spend all their studio time performing (although they certainly could), because they are also exploring writing, directing, design, and/or producing. I strongly encourage you to look more closely at Fordham–the manta is ‘learning by doing’ and grads leave ready to make their own work and create theatre at a high artistic level and with practical skills in multiple arenas.</p> 
               <p id="comment-like-813" data-liked="comment-not-liked" class="comment-likes comment-not-liked"><a href="http://onstageblog.com/2015/02/19/the-best-b-a-in-theatre-programs-in-the-country-in-2015/?like_comment=813&amp;_wpnonce=b7e85b4d2c" class="comment-like-link needs-login" rel="nofollow" data-blog="71050352"><span>Like</span></a><span id="comment-like-count-813" class="comment-like-feedback">Like</span></p> 
               <div class="reply"> 
               </div>
               <!-- .reply --> 
              </div> 
             </div>
             <!-- #comment-813 --> </li>
