        <li class="comment odd alt thread-even depth-1 highlander-comment" id="li-comment-633"> 
         <div id="comment-633" class="clear"> 
          <div class="comment-meta">
            John 
           <div class="comment-date">
            February 22, 2015
           </div> 
           <img alt="" src="http://2.gravatar.com/avatar/eb242114a8905969f2a09e2f78605167?s=55&amp;d=identicon&amp;r=G" class="avatar avatar-55" height="55" width="55"> 
          </div>
          <!-- .comment-meta --> 
          <div class="comment-content"> 
           <p>What is your criteria for this list? I think that there are many schools that could have been contenders. Is student to faculty ratio taken into account? Well rounded course opportunities? Focus in a specialty after Sophomore year? Student employment within department? Alumni success in the professional theatre? I think what I may be getting at it that a list of 10 is probably too small when the pool is so large.</p> 
           <p id="comment-like-633" data-liked="comment-not-liked" class="comment-likes comment-not-liked"><a href="http://onstageblog.com/2015/02/19/the-best-b-a-in-theatre-programs-in-the-country-in-2015/?like_comment=633&amp;_wpnonce=65e8475bf6" class="comment-like-link needs-login" rel="nofollow" data-blog="71050352"><span>Like</span></a><span id="comment-like-count-633" class="comment-like-feedback">Like</span></p> 
           <div class="reply"> 
            <a class="comment-reply-link" href="/2015/02/19/the-best-b-a-in-theatre-programs-in-the-country-in-2015/?replytocom=633#respond" onclick="return addComment.moveForm( &quot;comment-633&quot;, &quot;633&quot;, &quot;respond&quot;, &quot;1598&quot; )" aria-label="Reply to John">Reply</a> 
           </div>
           <!-- .reply --> 
          </div> 
         </div>
         <!-- #comment-633 --> </li>
        <!-- #comment-## --> 
        <li class="comment even thread-odd thread-alt depth-1 highlander-comment" id="li-comment-634"> 
         <div id="comment-634" class="clear"> 
          <div class="comment-meta"> 
           <a href="http://cas.umw.edu/theatre" rel="external nofollow" class="url">Jon Reynolds</a> 
           <div class="comment-date">
            February 22, 2015
           </div> 
           <img alt="" src="http://2.gravatar.com/avatar/ef8e170bdc849cb378e3beace6783708?s=55&amp;d=identicon&amp;r=G" class="avatar avatar-55" height="55" width="55"> 
          </div>
          <!-- .comment-meta --> 
          <div class="comment-content"> 
           <p>The University of Mary Washington / Fredericksburg, VA</p> 
           <p>In the boyhood home of George Washington lies a small University (named for his mother) offering a BA in Theatre stemming from a pleasingly varied and robust curriculum with the singular goal of preparing students for careers in the professional theatre. UMW Theatre provides the surrounding community with four productions a year (including at least one musical production) taking place in their newly-renovated and technologically advanced main stage space. The program also boasts an experimental black box theatre completely run by students, hosting bi-annual events such as a 24-Hour Play Festival and a week of 10 minute plays as well as many other productions and workshops throughout each year. </p> 
           <p>Students often take on major roles advised by master teachers, and are shaped by their expertise in lighting, scenic and costume design as well as direction, and of course, acting. A hallmark of the program is the stage management focus, providing stage managers with a skill set that has resulted in work at many major New York venues and nearby Washington, DC Theatres (The John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts, Ford’s Theatre).</p> 
           <p>Although a small, and not yet well-known university theatre program, the production values are on par with those of professional regional theaters across the country (due to the ability of the department to invite professional designers and technicians to teach and mentor the students). An increasing rarity of college theatre programs, there is absolutely no criteria for becoming an actor, and no audition is required for acceptance or involvement in the program. A student can conceivably land a leading role in their first week of classes.</p> 
           <p>Tuition is highly reasonable for in-state and out-of-state students and the student staff of the department management office is always excited to get a phone call or give a tour of the facilities (just another benefit to being a small program).</p> 
           <p>Recent productions have included Spring Awakening, Always…Patsy Cline, Lysistrata, Doubt, Sunday in the Park with George, and The Drunken City. </p> 
           <p>Alumni have acted professionally on Broadway (Legally Blonde, Kinky Boots) and on National tours (Motown, Legally Blonde), and professionally in Washington, DC (Studio Theatre, The Shakespeare Theatre Company), all attributing their successes to the skills developed at UMW.</p> 
           <p id="comment-like-634" data-liked="comment-not-liked" class="comment-likes comment-not-liked"><a href="http://onstageblog.com/2015/02/19/the-best-b-a-in-theatre-programs-in-the-country-in-2015/?like_comment=634&amp;_wpnonce=a7f40be95c" class="comment-like-link needs-login" rel="nofollow" data-blog="71050352"><span>Like</span></a><span id="comment-like-count-634" class="comment-like-feedback">Like</span></p> 
           <div class="reply"> 
            <a class="comment-reply-link" href="/2015/02/19/the-best-b-a-in-theatre-programs-in-the-country-in-2015/?replytocom=634#respond" onclick="return addComment.moveForm( &quot;comment-634&quot;, &quot;634&quot;, &quot;respond&quot;, &quot;1598&quot; )" aria-label="Reply to Jon Reynolds">Reply</a> 
           </div>
           <!-- .reply --> 
          </div> 
         </div>
         <!-- #comment-634 --> </li>
        <!-- #comment-## --> 
        <li class="post pingback"> <p>Pingback: <a href="http://www.drew.edu/news/2015/02/10/professor-lisa-brenner-named-co-editor-of-theatre-topics" rel="external nofollow" class="url">Professor Lisa Brenner Named Co-Editor of Theatre Topics | Drew Today | Drew University</a></p> </li>
        <!-- #comment-## --> 
        <li class="comment odd alt thread-even depth-1 highlander-comment" id="li-comment-823"> 
         <div id="comment-823" class="clear"> 
          <div class="comment-meta">
            NUstudent 
           <div class="comment-date">
            February 27, 2015
           </div> 
           <img alt="" src="http://2.gravatar.com/avatar/5304c00c0e8c2bbcf4d4009ef211006d?s=55&amp;d=identicon&amp;r=G" class="avatar avatar-55" height="55" width="55"> 
          </div>
          <!-- .comment-meta --> 
          <div class="comment-content"> 
           <p>I go to Northwestern and it should definitely be on this list! There are 4-6 shows happening every weekend, including 2-5 Wirtz (department) shows a quarter (we have three quarters per year). As a freshman who got here 20 weeks ago, I’ve had the opportunity to work on six shows already (though from a design/directing perspective, not onstage), and many of my freshman peers have acted in three or four productions already. We not only have a variety of student companies focused on specific niches within theatre– theatre for young audiences, theatre for social change, student written work, feminist theatre, classics, experimental theatre, to name a few– with fully functioning student executive boards, directors, producers, design teams, and actors, we have an incredible range of theatrical focus within the department. Our major includes acting, design, and theory requirements, and we can choose to take one of six modules (I believe they are TYA, playwriting, devising and adaptation, theatre management, theatre design, and musical theatre choreography). The classes are small from the beginning (I had a 16 person voice for performance/IPA class my first quarter here) and the large theatre faculty is extremely qualified (most of them work professionally in Chicago) and so open to communicating and working with undergraduates. The school is traditionally acting-oriented, but everything else is catching up fast. Thanks to Laura Schellhardt, our playwriting program really is top notch. The focus here is on well-rounded, smart theatre makers who produce informed work in all capacities. The connections it provides to the theatre scene at large (especially to the “purple mafia” in Chicago) are invaluable. One of our seniors, who will be graduating in June, just got cast in a Steppenwolf show for the summer! Others have gone on to Second City, SNL, Broadway, you name it. It truly is one of the best places to be a theatre major.</p> 
           <p id="comment-like-823" data-liked="comment-not-liked" class="comment-likes comment-not-liked"><a href="http://onstageblog.com/2015/02/19/the-best-b-a-in-theatre-programs-in-the-country-in-2015/?like_comment=823&amp;_wpnonce=d5fbd61c5a" class="comment-like-link needs-login" rel="nofollow" data-blog="71050352"><span>Like</span></a><span id="comment-like-count-823" class="comment-like-feedback">Like</span></p> 
           <div class="reply"> 
            <a class="comment-reply-link" href="/2015/02/19/the-best-b-a-in-theatre-programs-in-the-country-in-2015/?replytocom=823#respond" onclick="return addComment.moveForm( &quot;comment-823&quot;, &quot;823&quot;, &quot;respond&quot;, &quot;1598&quot; )" aria-label="Reply to NUstudent">Reply</a> 
           </div>
           <!-- .reply --> 
          </div> 
         </div>
         <!-- #comment-823 --> </li>
